bald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":75,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":84,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":119,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Butler was born about 1140, in Cornwall, England. He married Matilda de Teynham. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1140–Deceased":"umbes 1140–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1199–Female":"1199–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"about 1140–Deceased":"noin 1140–Kuollut","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1199–Female":"1199–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","about 1140":"noin 1140","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"about 1140–Deceased":"environ 1140–Décédé","1173–Female":"1173–Décédée","1199–Female":"1199–Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","about 1140":"environ 1140","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Butler est né env